WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.040
 Hello and welcome to another walkthrough for computer architecture for everybody.

00:00:04.040 --> 00:00:08.920
 In this walkthrough we are going to talk about WASM and we're going to talk a little bit

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:10.720
 about the hello world code.

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.760
 Now the first thing to say is that WASM, now Watt is just a sort of syntax, it's the assembly

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:22.280
 language for the machine language and the first thing to say is that unlike microprocessors

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:26.680
 and assembly language and machine language it was never intended to be handwritten and

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:31.160
 so this is a lot less convenient than even assembly language.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:38.960
 Its goal is to be sort of verifiable and safe because JavaScript and WASM are intended to

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:44.520
 run with code from many different sources that doesn't necessarily want to trust each

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:48.640
 other or have one piece of code affect the other piece of code.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:53.600
 So it has this concept of sandboxed execution so that no matter what you do in your little

00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:58.140
 sandbox you can take stuff in and give stuff back but in your sandbox you can't sort of

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:01.760
 mess with anybody else's sandbox so there's a goal of isolation.

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:05.820
 So this language is designed for like isolation first.

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:11.960
 It's designed to not allow you to write code that could touch memory that doesn't belong

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:16.340
 to you or anything like that and so it's about this isolation.

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:20.920
 The actual code model, first off you can see that it's very parenthesis based and the parenthesis

00:01:20.920 --> 00:01:23.720
 are kind of like curly braces, they're beginnings and ends.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:29.340
 So what we're looking at is Hello World WASM, it's not C, AI gave me just some simple Hello

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:30.340
 World WASM.

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:35.620
 Now in this case we are using things like console.log from JavaScript and passing into

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:39.600
 that console the log message and the length of the log message.

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:46.320
 So this is code that is expecting to run in a JavaScript environment and that console.log

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:47.520
 will be available to it.

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:52.980
 And so there's an import statement that basically says pull in some code from JavaScript or

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:59.960
 give me access to a log function from console.log function from JavaScript itself.

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:03.120
 We're going to declare that we need some memory, we're going to fill that memory up starting

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:05.720
 at zero with the string Hello World.

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:10.880
 These are actually not zero terminated, this is really a string that's 13 long and you'll

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:16.960
 see this 13 come in in a second and then we're going to make it so that the memory is available

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:19.060
 to the JavaScript that's going to call us.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:24.340
 And then we have a main function that's going to be called by the JavaScript and we're going

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:28.860
 to call our log function and pass the string and the length of the string and then we're

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:33.120
 going to return 42 even main functions like in C return values and then we're going to

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:37.560
 export the function main and then there's JavaScript that's going to call this function

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:38.560
 main.

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:40.500
 So let's go ahead and compile and run this.

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:47.480
 In this browser there is a full Watt to Wasm compiler and then Wasm to machine code and

00:02:47.480 --> 00:02:52.000
 then JavaScript to execute the resulting machine code.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:53.840
 And here is the actual Wasm.

00:02:53.840 --> 00:03:00.200
 So Watt is sort of the assembly language but the ultimate thing is this is just a few bytes

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:06.920
 looks like about 6 times 16 about 100 bytes of character and these are these are kind

00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:12.080
 of like machine code but it is interpreted so this is kind of like a byte code in Java

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:16.680
 but it's also intended that it can be just in time compiled into the real machine code

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:19.840
 after validating the safety of it.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:27.600
 And so we go from the Watt to the Wasm and then we execute this Wasm in JavaScript and

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:33.800
 JavaScript has a Wasm execution environment for it and then the output comes back to JavaScript

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:35.240
 and away we go.

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:42.080
 So that is the hello world simple hello world not a C hello world I'll show you that in

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:49.200
 a bit but a Wasm and JavaScript hello world that does its printing using console.log.

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:50.280
 Cheers.

